<span class="comment"><font color=#000000>Easier to remember is the bisection method: essentially, a binary search for where the graph crosses the x-axis. It's what I would have pulled out if I got asked the square root problem in an interview:<p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection_method" rel="nofollow">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection_method</a></font></span><p><font size=1><font color=#f6f6ef>-----</font></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table border=0><tr><td><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/s.gif" height=1 width=160></td><td valign=top><center><a id=up_3427862 href="vote?for=3427862&dir=up&whence=%69%74%65%6d%3f%69%64%3d%33%34%32%34%38%36%32"><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/grayarrow.gif" border=0 vspace=3 hspace=2></a><span id=down_3427862></span></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px; "><span class="comhead"><a href="user?id=sgk284">sgk284</a> 179 days ago  | <a href="item?id=3427862">link</a></span></div><br>
