<span class="comment"><font color=#000000>I'm willing to bet on-site engineers (especially those with H1B1s) are more loyal. It cuts both ways though - a freelancer knows they are first to go if they company needs to cut back.</font></span><p><font size=1><font color=#f6f6ef>-----</font></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table border=0><tr><td><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/s.gif" height=1 width=80></td><td valign=top><center><a id=up_3427449 href="vote?for=3427449&dir=up&whence=%69%74%65%6d%3f%69%64%3d%33%34%32%34%38%36%32"><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/grayarrow.gif" border=0 vspace=3 hspace=2></a><span id=down_3427449></span></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px; "><span class="comhead"><a href="user?id=krallja">krallja</a> 179 days ago  | <a href="item?id=3427449">link</a></span></div><br>
<span class="comment"><font color=#000000>Freelancing is not the same thing as a remote employee.</font></span><p><font size=1><font color=#f6f6ef>-----</font></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr style="height:10px"></tr><tr><td class="title"><a href="/x?fnid=YjB5RZdX2f" rel="nofollow">More</a></td></tr></table><br><br>
